  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Frameworks\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate to investigate and prosecute money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Extradition agreements\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n\n4. Standardization of Regulations\n- Harmonizing legal definitions of money laundering\n- Establishing consistent reporting protocols\n- Creating cross-border enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International economic sanctions against countries with weak AML frameworks\n- Asset freezing and seizure\n- Coordinated legal actions\n\n6. Information Sharing Mechanisms\n- Global financial intelligence networks\n- Interpol and international law enforcement cooperation\n- Digital platforms for tracking suspicious transactions\n\n7. Jurisdictional Challenges\n- Addressing differences in legal systems\n- Resolving conflicts between national laws\n- Creating transnational legal frameworks\n\nThese intersections aim to create comprehensive strategies for preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
